label chapter3:

    # [Scene: Town Hall (Retrofitted Gymnasium) | Evening]

    scene bg ch3_98c6f2_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmurs; the scrape of chairs; a kettle somewhere behind the hall. A distant, muffled thunder—more a promise than a storm yet.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense BGM — cello tremor under a thin electronic pulse]
    "Narration:"
    "You step up to the podium with the weight of the last few days in your shoulders like wet fabric. The Moleskine is open to the maps you drew in the margins of four sleepless nights:"
    "restoration mats outlined in shaky ink, predicted tide-lines annotated with urgent dates. The light from the projection flattens colors; your linen blouse looks softer than it feels. The room breathes—hot coffee and dust and the metallic"
    "tang of nerves—and every face is angled toward you as if you were the fulcrum."
    "Your hand is steady on the podium even though your pulse drums a different cadence. Eight days. Ava's model flashed that number; you can hear it now, a metronome behind your ribs. Eight days until the"
    "next window of storm probability tightens into a forecast you cannot ignore. Eight days to choose a direction that will decide who keeps their home, who keeps their nets, who loses the small reclamations of livelihood"
    "that line the bay."
    "Your hand is steady on the podium even though your pulse drums a different cadence. Eight days. Ava's model flashed that number; you can hear it now, a metronome behind your ribs. Eight days until the"
    "next window of storm probability tightens into a forecast you cannot ignore. Eight days to choose a direction that will decide who keeps their home, who keeps their nets, who loses the small reclamations of livelihood"
    "that line the bay."
    show mayor_rosa_santiago at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_rosa_santiago "Maia—take it from the top. People need the facts, and they need to know what you think."
    show maia_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "Thank you. I'll be concise. I'll outline the ecological options, the timelines, and the likely impacts as best we can—"
    show elias_wren at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_wren "—and the funding that makes those timelines possible. We'll show you projected flood-lines after implementation. Our platform reduces regional inundation by thirty-seven percent."
    "Narration:"
    "Elias Wren's voice folds into the room like a clinical tide—precise, certain. The AR schematic hums; a slick cross-section unfurls on the screen: armored seawall, pylons beyond the surf, a lattice of offshore turbines. The lights"
    "from the projection paint his face a cool steel gray, and you feel a jolt of something like betrayal—because the plan is beautiful in a way that doesn't belong here."
    hide mayor_rosa_santiago
    show jonah_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_kade "Beautiful doesn't fish, Elias. You put that thing up and you change currents. You change where the fish go. You tell me which nets will be empty next season."

    elias_wren "We model those impacts. Migration shifts are accounted for—' (he gestures, AR layers toggling) '—and mitigation strategies are baked into the deployment schedule."

    "Jonah Kade (cutting him off)" "Mitigation isn't the same as home. You've got models; we've got lifetimes."
    "Narration:"
    "The exchange rips a seam in the room. Heads turn toward Jonah Kade: loyalty tightening his jaw. Lupe leans forward, urgency in her voice like a fast tide."
    hide maia_rivera
    show lupe_kade at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lupe_kade "Jobs. He says mitigation; I hear promises. My ledger here—' (she slaps the cooperative records, light thudding the wood) '—shows families balancing on seasonal income. If there's real funding for local labor, I need to see binding commitments, not a slide deck."

    "Dana (hard, a smudge of paint still on her knuckles)" "He's colonizing the coastline. Meridian's idea of rescue is to buy control. You think we don't remember how outsiders use 'resilience' to take what they want?"
    "Narration:"
    "Dana's accusation hangs like a flag in a windless corridor. It lands on you with the weight of all the compromises you have counted and rejected in private. You can feel the room tilting along a fault line: practical hope clashing with fear, money against memory."

    "Mayor Rosa (pinched, diplomatic)" "We have to be careful with language. False accusations can sink civic process faster than tides.' (she looks to you) 'Maia—what's the timeline, scientifically? What can community action achieve before any construction could begin?"
    hide elias_wren
    show maia_rivera at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "Community-led restoration can increase marsh elevation and buffer storm surge locally—measurable benefits within months to a couple of years depending on funding and labor. But it doesn't replace engineered hard infrastructure for immediate, large-scale protection. The models—' (you glance at Ava; the tablet light makes her face a pale island) '—Ava's storm window shows high-confidence risk in eight days. Waiting to build or reconfigure large structures leaves us exposed."

    menu:
        "Lean into the maps: emphasize short-term, practical restoration steps now":
            "You describe, in clipped sentences, a week-by-week mobilization: community crews, donated materials, an emergency fundraising drive. The room quiets as people picture hands in the mud. Tomas nods once, precise. Lupe scribbles numbers. Jonah Kade's jaw loosens minutely—hope that is brittle but real."
        "Call for a brief procedural pause to coordinate with Ava on the storm models":
            "You ask Ava to bring up the latest runs. For a moment the technical language blankets the room: isobars, confidence intervals. Faces that are used to weather read numbers like prayers. Mayor Rosa appreciates the rigor; Dana sneers softly, interpreting delay as deference."
        "Step aside and invite Elias to detail funding guarantees before you continue":
            "You gesture to Elias Wren to lay out concrete funding strings. He does, with contractual precision. Some in the crowd lean forward at the word 'secured.' Others fold their arms, the word 'secured' feeling like chains. You feel the moral weight of one phrase—'secured funding'—press into your sternum."

    # --- merge ---
    "The room adjusts to your chosen framing; conversations shift around the new center."
    "Narration:"
    "You choose words and gestures that matter; every breath you take is parsed for political altitude. The micro-choice ripples outward—someone's hope swells, someone else's suspicion tightens. Your chest is a drum now, counting down more insistently than Ava's models."

    "Ava (speaking up, voice steady but quiet)" "The model isn't a prophecy. It shows increasing probability. If we accelerate community measures now, we can lower exposure for certain neighborhoods. If construction begins immediately, there are engineering mitigations for migration impacts, but they require enforceable oversight and periodic reassessment. Those safeguards are not automatic."

    "Elias Wren (measured, a slight lift of the chin)" "Oversight can be codified. We can write adaptive management into the contract—third-party audits, community liaisons."
    hide jonah_kade
    show dana_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dana_park "And who picks those third parties? You? Meridian? We don't need another name on our shoreline deciding whether our kids get to fish."

    maia_rivera "We need enforceable oversight if any external project proceeds. And we need an accelerated, organized community response now to protect the most vulnerable shorelines before the storm window narrows."

    "Mayor Rosa (her voice falters a fraction)" "That sounds reasonable—"

    "Jonah Kade (cutting across, urgency rising)" "—'Enforceable' is a word until it's on paper and signed. We need names, timelines, people on the ground. Otherwise it's lipstick on a seawall."

    "Elias Wren (defensive now)" "We are willing to include community oversight. We have lawyers, we have teams—"

    "Dana (bitter)" "You have teams that move in with flood maps and move out with boardwalks in their contract clauses."
    "Narration:"
    "The tempo in the room accelerates; the threads of conversation snag and fray. You can feel it: if you don't take a clear stance, the town fractures into smaller arguments, each one a crack that could turn into a breach during the next storm."

    "Tomas (voice small but anchored)" "Whatever you decide, Maia, remember the people who can't rebuild if they lose what's left. Don't let paperwork replace the folks who live here."

    lupe_kade "And if we can get training and labor vouchers, I can mobilize the cooperative. But Maia—we need to know you're all-in."

    "Jonah Kade (looking at you, sea-glass eyes dark)" "Maia. Say what you mean. We can't have platitudes. Either you stand with the bay and its people, or you sign away the nets."
    "Narration:"
    "Jonah Kade's accusation is a lance and a plea at once. You see for a splayed second the memory that sits behind it: your hands in mud as a girl, the boathouse being lifted and torn."
    "Your guilt blooms: have you been so busy measuring and mediating that you forgot to choose who you serve?"

    menu:
        "Answer Jonah directly, naming the people and places you intend to protect":
            "You draw breath and name them: the fish house on Pier C, Tomas's row of storage sheds, Lupe's ledger and the families it represents. Jonah Kade closes his eyes for a heartbeat, the lines on his face softening like kelp in a current. Some in the crowd sniff as if holding back tears."
        "Deflect with technical specifics about adaptation timelines":
            "You pivot to timelines—months, weeks, material needs. The room listens, but the emotional edge dulls; faces settle into careful pragmatism. Jonah Kade's fingers curl around the back of a chair; he doesn't smile."

    # --- merge ---
    "The room responds differently depending on the directness of your appeal; trust shifts incrementally."
    "Narration:"
    "You measure the room and the people in it the way you measure marsh elevation—by layers and compaction, by what will hold under pressure. The storm window edges closer in your head. Ava's tablet chirps softly;"
    "the model's latest run completes like a small, immovable metronome. The glow from the screen silhouettes Elias Wren, who remains composed, offering engineered certainties; yet the crowd is human and messy and needs a leader who"
    "will carry the moral weight, not slide it into a contract."
    "Your chest tightens until your ribs feel like a cage that might crack. Guilt curdles into urgency, urgency into a sharp, jagged choice that will tilt every tide-line you have sketched. You can hear Tomas's cane again, tapping out a steady, unforgiving tempo: act."

    "Mayor Rosa (soft, decisive)" "We need a town position tonight. Maia—what is our stance? We can't leave the council guessing."
    "Narration:"
    "All of the noises converge—the coughs, the whispering papers, Jonah Kade's chair creaking as he shifts his weight, Dana's folded arms. The hall seems to narrow to the space around you. Your heartbeat is a drumbeat in your ears, louder than all the murmurs—fast, insistent, the only metronome that matters."
    "You know what each path will entail in broad strokes: mobilize the town now with brutal, immediate labor and scarce funding; negotiate a hybrid with concessions and oversight that binds people to legal strings; or buy"
    "time and hope a quieter, forensic search of Elias Wren's impact studies reveals clear compromises. Each choice contains cost and salvage, risk and moral calculus. Each will change the town, and you, irrevocably."

    menu:
        "Look into the crowd and speak from the heart—declare immediate community action":
            "Your voice is raw but steady. You invoke Tomas's stories, Lupe's ledgers, Jonah Kade's hands and the smell of the boathouse. The room leans in; for half a breath you see realignment—neighbors nodding, hands opening to help. But Dana's face hardens; Elias Wren's jaw tightens like a clamped gate."
        "Turn to Elias and say you'll open negotiations with strict oversight conditions":
            "You set terms aloud: third-party audits, community vetoes on sensitive zones, binding labor commitments. The room registers the attempt at a bridge—some relief, some skepticism. Elias Wren inclines his head, expression unreadable; Jonah Kade's posture relaxes fractionally, suspicious but curious."
        "Ask for a 72-hour pause and privately task Ava to audit the studies":
            "You ask for time. Ava meets your eyes—she is tired but nods. The hall shifts; some interpret the delay as prudence, others as weakness. Dana's lips press into a thin line; Lupe squirms with impatience. Mayor Rosa writes the request down with a hand that trembles just enough to be human."

    # --- merge ---
    "Each path sets the town's immediate trajectory; consequences unfold in later scenes."
    "Narration:"
    "The air in the room is electric with accusation and possibility. The storm clock hammers at your back. You can smell the salt through the windows, feel the draft that will bring rain if you wait too late. Your throat is tight; your hands damp on the podium."
    "Everything accumulates into one thin, impossible question: what will you ask this town to be for itself tonight? Your choice will not only shift policy—it will bend the arteries of personal lives: Jonah Kade's livelihood, Lupe's work, Tomas's safety, Dana's trust, the very fabric of Marisol Bay."
    "You look at Jonah Kade—his eyes unreadable, a storm of hurt and hope behind them. You look at Elias Wren—his composure like a seawall, elegant but alien. You look at Ava—steady, exhausted, a scientist with a"
    "model that beeps and demands truth. You look at the names in your Moleskine and hear the gulls wheel like a chorus holding its breath."
    "Your heartbeat climbs to a peak, every collision of argument and memory amplifying the pressure. The room is silent in a way that vibrates; it's the silence before a very loud tide."
    "Choose your stance. Decide the public pathway for Marisol Bay."
    "I call for an immediate community-led restoration plan, rejecting the corporate proposal."
    "I open formal negotiations with Elias Wren for a partnership, seeking concessions."
    "I ask for more time and quietly task Ava to audit Elias Wren's impact studies—seek truth before choosing."

